const Q_PHE_2025_MODEL_I=[{"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Why do sprinters lean forward during the start?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To look at the finish line</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To push forcefully forward</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To balance better</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To reduce air resistance</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">During the start of a sprint, sprinters adopt a forward-leaning posture primarily to direct the force they generate horizontally into forward motion. When the body leans forward, the athlete's center of gravity is positioned ahead of the base of support, encouraging a powerful drive phase that propels them forward. This forward lean optimizes the angle at which the sprinter applies force against the ground, maximizing horizontal acceleration while minimizing vertical force that would otherwise waste energy lifting the body unnecessarily. If the sprinter were fully upright at the start, the force exerted would not translate as effectively into forward propulsion, resulting in a slower acceleration phase. The forward lean also helps maintain balance during the explosive push off the blocks. While looking at the finish line or reducing air resistance might be beneficial later in the race, the start focuses on maximizing acceleration through forceful horizontal movement.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: ATHLETICS (TRACK AND FIELD EVENTS) : TRACK EVENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which phase comes right after the reaction time in sprinting?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Drive phase</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Maximum velocity phase</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Finish phase</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Relaxation phase</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The drive phase is the stage immediately following the reaction time, where the sprinter moves from a stationary position into acceleration. After hearing the starting gun, the sprinter reacts by initiating forceful movements to gain speed as quickly as possible. In this phase, the athlete remains in a slightly forward-leaning posture, applying powerful horizontal forces against the track to overcome inertia. The drive phase typically lasts for the first 20 to 30 meters of the race and focuses on maximizing acceleration through rapid, forceful strides with longer ground contact times to generate propulsion. It is critical because the speed attained here largely determines the final outcome of the race. Following the drive phase, the sprinter transitions into the maximum velocity phase, where the posture becomes more upright and stride frequency increases. Understanding the role of the drive phase allows athletes to optimize training for explosive power and acceleration.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: ATHLETICS (TRACK AND FIELD EVENTS) : TRACK EVENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Why do runners try to minimize ground contact time?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To rest longer on each step</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To reduce energy use</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To increase speed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To jump higher</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ground contact time is the duration a runner's foot stays in contact with the track during each step. Minimizing this time is critical for sprinting because it allows the legs to cycle faster, resulting in increased stride frequency and thus higher speed. Short ground contact times indicate that the athlete is applying force rapidly and effectively against the ground, propelling the body forward with minimal delay. Conversely, longer ground contact times slow down running because the runner spends more time decelerating and less time moving forward. Efficient sprinters develop neuromuscular adaptations that enable rapid force generation and quick turnover, while still applying enough force to maintain stride length. Training drills, such as plyometrics and sprint technique work, often focus on reducing ground contact time to improve overall velocity.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: ATHLETICS (TRACK AND FIELD EVENTS) : TRACK EVENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">How does aerobic energy contribute to track events?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Provides energy for short sprints</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Helps with long-distance events</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Only used for walking</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Used during rest</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The aerobic energy system relies on oxygen to produce ATP and is the predominant source of energy during long-duration, lower-intensity activities such as middle-distance and long-distance running events (e.g., 1500m, 5000m, marathon). Unlike sprint events, where energy must be supplied rapidly and anaerobically, aerobic metabolism supports sustained energy output over extended periods. The aerobic system uses carbohydrates, fats, and sometimes proteins as fuel, generating large quantities of ATP but at a slower rate than anaerobic systems. Aerobic conditioning improves the body's ability to deliver oxygen to muscles via increased capillary density, mitochondrial size, and efficiency, which delays fatigue during longer events. While minimal in short sprints, aerobic capacity is important for recovery between training bouts and repeated sprint efforts.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: ATHLETICS (TRACK AND FIELD EVENTS) : TRACK EVENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is a key phase in the long jump?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 'approach run', where the athlete builds up speed and prepares for takeoff.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 'crossover step', where the athlete crosses their legs to build momentum.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 'double arm swing', where the athlete swings both arms to increase height.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 'glide' phase, where the athlete glides across the pit.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The long jump is composed of several key phases, with the approach run being one of the most important. During the approach run, the athlete sprints down the runway to generate horizontal velocity. The speed built up during this phase is crucial because it directly influences the distance of the jump — the faster and more controlled the approach, the greater the potential jump distance. The athlete must balance between running fast and maintaining control to ensure an accurate takeoff from the board without fouling.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: ATHLETICS (TRACK AND FIELD EVENTS) : FIELD EVENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> In the discus throw, what is a key element of the athlete's technique?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Throwing the discus from a stationary position without any rotation.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Using a spinning motion to build angular momentum before the release.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jumping over a barrier and then throwing the discus.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Running a long approach and then throwing the discus like a javelin.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The discus throw is a complex field event where the athlete aims to throw a heavy disc-shaped implement as far as possible. A critical element of discus technique is the use of a spinning motion to generate angular momentum before releasing the discus. The athlete begins inside a throwing circle and performs one and a half rapid rotations (or spins) while maintaining balance and control. This rotational movement helps to build up angular velocity, which translates into the kinetic energy transferred to the discus at release. <br/>  <br/> The spinning motion maximizes the amount of force the athlete can apply to the discus, resulting in greater release speed and thus longer throws. It requires a high degree of coordination, balance, and timing to execute effectively. Athletes also use the spin to optimize the discus's angle of release, which affects aerodynamics and flight distance.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: ATHLETICS (TRACK AND FIELD EVENTS) : FIELD EVENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the pole vault, what is the 'plant' phase?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The moment the athlete plants their head on the mat after the jump.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The moment the athlete plants their hands on the pole before the jump.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The moment the athlete plants their feet in the takeoff box to stop their forward motion.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The moment the pole is placed in the 'plant box' on the ground.</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 'plant' phase in pole vaulting refers to the critical moment when the athlete places the pole into the 'plant box'—a metal or fiberglass trough embedded in the runway just before the takeoff point. This action is fundamental because it allows the vaulter to convert the horizontal speed generated during the approach run into vertical lift to clear the bar. <br/>  <br/> The pole acts like a spring, bending as it stores elastic energy during the plant and takeoff. A well-timed and precise plant ensures that the pole bends correctly, enabling the athlete to use the stored energy to propel themselves upwards. The plant requires coordination, strength, and excellent timing. If the pole is not planted correctly—too early, too late, or at the wrong angle—it can result in loss of momentum, a failed vault, or even injury.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: ATHLETICS (TRACK AND FIELD EVENTS) : FIELD EVENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the long jump, a foul occurs if the athlete's foot touches what part of the takeoff board?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The red warning strip on the side of the runway.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Any part of the sand pit before the jump.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ground beyond the front edge of the takeoff board.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Any part of the takeoff board before the white line.</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the long jump, the takeoff board is a critical element used to measure legal jumps. It is a white rectangular board embedded at the end of the runway. Just beyond the front edge of the takeoff board is a red or plasticine foul line (often called the \"foul line\" or \"warning strip\"), which is used to detect fouls. <br/>  <br/> A foul occurs if any part of the athlete's foot crosses beyond the front edge of the takeoff board during takeoff—meaning the athlete steps on or beyond the foul line before launching into the jump. When this happens, the jump is disqualified because the athlete effectively shortens the jump distance by taking off closer to the landing pit than allowed, which provides an unfair advantage.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: ATHLETICS (TRACK AND FIELD EVENTS) : FIELD EVENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One of the key principles of PE is 'individuality.' This principle suggests that a PE program should be tailored to account for:</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The unique abilities, interests, needs, and backgrounds of each student.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The uniform performance standards for all students in the class.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The latest trends and popular sports in the media.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The school's athletic team's needs and training schedules.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Principle of Individuality in Physical Education recognizes that every student is different in terms of physical capabilities, interests, learning pace, cultural backgrounds, and health status. A one-size-fits-all approach to PE does not effectively serve the diverse needs of students. Instead, PE programs should be designed to accommodate these individual differences, allowing each student to progress at a suitable pace and engage in activities that motivate and challenge them appropriately. <br/>  <br/> Tailoring PE programs according to individuality ensures that students receive personalized attention that promotes their physical development, enhances motivation, reduces the risk of injury, and fosters lifelong engagement in physical activity. Ignoring this principle can lead to frustration for slower learners or boredom for those who require more advanced challenges.</div>", "topic": "FOUNDATIONS AND PRINCIPLES OF PHYSICAL AND HEALTH EDUCATION: PRINCIPLES, MEANING, SCOPE AND PHILOSOPHY OF PHYSICAL EDUCATION (PE) : HISTORY AND DEVELOPMENT OF PE IN ANCIENT GREECE (SPARTA, ATHENS) AND ROME"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A physical education program that emphasizes the development of an individual's physical, mental, social, and emotional attributes is based on a philosophy of:</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Competition-driven education</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Body-centric education</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Holistic education</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Skill-based education</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Holistic education is a philosophy that views the individual as an integrated whole, emphasizing balanced development across multiple domains: physical, mental, social, and emotional. In the context of Physical Education (PE), this approach recognizes that optimal human development does not focus solely on physical fitness or skill acquisition but also nurtures emotional well-being, cognitive growth, and social interaction. <br/>  <br/> This philosophy supports activities that promote physical health alongside mental clarity, emotional resilience, and interpersonal skills, fostering well-rounded individuals who can lead healthy and fulfilling lives. It contrasts with philosophies that focus narrowly on physical prowess (body-centric) or competition alone.</div>", "topic": "FOUNDATIONS AND PRINCIPLES OF PHYSICAL AND HEALTH EDUCATION: PRINCIPLES, MEANING, SCOPE AND PHILOSOPHY OF PHYSICAL EDUCATION (PE) : DEFINITIONS, SCOPE AND PHILOSOPHY OF PHYSICAL EDUCATION (PE)"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The scope of physical education includes health-related fitness. What does this primarily focus on?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ability to perform daily tasks with vigor and without undue fatigue.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Achieving a world-class level of physical performance in a single sport.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Learning about the history of physical education from ancient Greece to the present day.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ability to perform complex motor skills with precision and grace.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Health-related fitness is a key component within the scope of physical education, emphasizing the capacity of individuals to carry out everyday activities energetically and efficiently without undue exhaustion. This includes components such as cardiovascular endurance, muscular strength, muscular endurance, flexibility, and body composition. <br/>  <br/> The goal is to enhance the functional health and well-being of individuals so they can manage daily life demands, such as climbing stairs, carrying groceries, or working without premature tiredness. Health-related fitness promotes longevity, disease prevention, and overall quality of life.</div>", "topic": "FOUNDATIONS AND PRINCIPLES OF PHYSICAL AND HEALTH EDUCATION: PRINCIPLES, MEANING, SCOPE AND PHILOSOPHY OF PHYSICAL EDUCATION (PE) : DEFINITIONS, SCOPE AND PHILOSOPHY OF PHYSICAL EDUCATION (PE)"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which skill in football is used to legally take the ball away from an opponent?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Dribbling</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Passing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tackling</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Heading</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tackling is the defensive skill where a player attempts to dispossess an opponent of the ball legally. Proper tackling involves timing, positioning, and controlled contact without committing a foul. It is crucial in regaining possession and disrupting the opposing team's attack. Heading involves using the head to control or pass the ball, not taking it away from an opponent.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: BALL GAMES -FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL : SKILLS IN FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In basketball, which skill is used to quickly change direction while maintaining control of the ball?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Jump shot</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pivoting</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Dribbling</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rebounding</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pivoting is the technique of rotating the body on one foot (pivot foot) while keeping the other foot stationary, allowing the player to change direction without traveling (illegal movement). It helps maintain possession, create passing angles, and avoid defenders.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: BALL GAMES -FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL : SKILLS IN FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In basketball, what constitutes a 'traveling' violation?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Dribbling with both hands simultaneously</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Taking more than two steps without dribbling</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Passing the ball illegally</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Blocking a shot</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Traveling occurs when a player moves their feet excessively without dribbling the ball. This violation stops play, and the opposing team is awarded possession. Proper footwork and dribbling are essential to avoid traveling.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: BALL GAMES -FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL : RULES, REGULATIONS AND OFFICIATING IN FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL."}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In football, what is the difference between a direct free kick and an indirect free kick?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A direct free kick is awarded for less serious fouls, while an indirect free kick is for more serious fouls.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A direct free kick can score a goal directly, while an indirect free kick requires a second player to touch the ball before a goal can be scored.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A direct free kick is given to the defending team, and an indirect free kick is given to the attacking team.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A direct free kick is taken from a different part of the field than an indirect free kick.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In football, the key difference between a direct and indirect free kick lies in how a goal can be scored from them. A direct free kick allows the kicker to attempt to score directly without the ball touching another player first. It is awarded for more serious fouls such as handball, tripping, or charging. <br/>  <br/> An indirect free kick, however, means the ball must touch another player—either a teammate or an opponent—before a goal can count. It is typically awarded for less serious or technical offenses, such as dangerous play without contact or offside infractions. The referee signals an indirect free kick by raising an arm above their head until the kick is taken and the ball touches another player or goes out of play. <br/>  <br/> Understanding this difference is crucial for players and officials because it affects how the kick is taken and how the opposing team sets up their defense.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: BALL GAMES -FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL : RULES, REGULATIONS AND OFFICIATING IN FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL."}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An athlete preparing for a marathon should focus on consuming a diet rich in:</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fats, to build and repair muscle tissues.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Complex carbohydrates, to provide a sustained release of energy.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Vitamins, to regulate body temperature.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Proteins, to provide quick energy for the race.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">For endurance events like marathons, athletes need a steady and prolonged supply of energy to maintain performance over long periods. Complex carbohydrates — found in whole grains, legumes, vegetables, and some fruits — are ideal because they break down slowly during digestion, releasing glucose gradually into the bloodstream. This steady glucose availability helps maintain stable blood sugar levels and provides sustained energy throughout the race. <br/>  <br/> While fats are also an important energy source, they are primarily utilized during low to moderate intensity activity and do not provide quick energy needed for high endurance. Fats are also essential for muscle repair, but during the marathon preparation phase, the focus is on maximizing glycogen stores (the stored form of carbohydrates in muscles and liver) to delay fatigue. <br/>  <br/> Proteins mainly serve the function of repairing and building muscle tissues but are not a primary energy source during long-distance running. Consuming excessive protein for energy is inefficient and can strain the digestive system. <br/>  <br/> Vitamins are vital for overall health and metabolic processes but do not directly provide energy or regulate body temperature in the context of race preparation. <br/>  <br/> Therefore, a diet rich in complex carbohydrates is crucial for marathon runners to optimize endurance performance by ensuring a reliable energy source.</div>", "topic": "FOOD, NUTRITION AND DRUGS: FOOD : CLASSES, SOURCES AND IMPORTANCE OF FOOD NUTRIENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is an example of a healthy fat source for an athlete?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Avocados and nuts.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fried foods and pastries.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Margarine and processed snacks.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Butter and red meat.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Healthy fats are essential for athletes because they provide a dense source of energy, support cell function, and help absorb fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, and K). They also contribute to hormone production and have anti-inflammatory properties which can aid recovery. <br/>  <br/> Avocados and nuts are rich in unsaturated fats, particularly monounsaturated and polyunsaturated fats, which are considered heart-healthy fats. These fats can improve cholesterol levels, reduce inflammation, and provide essential fatty acids like omega-3 and omega-6, which the body cannot produce on its own. <br/>  <br/> In contrast, fried foods and pastries typically contain trans fats and excessive saturated fats, which can increase the risk of heart disease and negatively impact an athlete's health and performance. <br/>  <br/> Margarine and processed snacks often contain artificial trans fats and unhealthy additives, which should be minimized in an athlete's diet. <br/>  <br/> Butter and red meat contain higher amounts of saturated fats, which, in moderation, can be part of a balanced diet but are not the healthiest fat sources when compared to unsaturated fats from plant-based foods. <br/>  <br/> For optimal performance and health, athletes should focus on including healthy fat sources such as avocados, nuts, seeds, fatty fish, and olive oil.</div>", "topic": "FOOD, NUTRITION AND DRUGS: FOOD : CLASSES, SOURCES AND IMPORTANCE OF FOOD NUTRIENTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is a skill-related component of physical fitness that is crucial for a basketball player to quickly change direction?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Agility</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Speed</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Power</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Reaction time</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Agility is defined as the ability to rapidly and accurately change the direction of the body while maintaining balance and control. This component is especially important in sports like basketball where players must frequently change direction quickly to evade opponents, make plays, or defend. <br/>  <br/> While speed refers to how fast a player can move in a straight line, it does not capture the ability to change directions quickly. Power is the ability to exert force quickly, useful for explosive movements like jumping or sprinting but not specifically for directional changes. Reaction time is the time taken to respond to a stimulus, important for initiating movement but not for the physical execution of changing direction. <br/>  <br/> Therefore, agility is the key skill-related component enabling a basketball player to make quick, precise movements on the court.</div>", "topic": "PHYSICAL FITNESS AND CONDITIONING PROGRAMMES: PHYSICAL FITNESS : COMPONENTS OF PHYSICAL FITNESS –HEALTHRELATED AND PERFORMANCE/SKILL-RELATED"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following activities is the best example of passive recreation?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Walking through a garden.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Watching a live performance at a theater.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Going for a run in the morning.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Playing tennis with a friend.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Passive recreation involves activities that require minimal physical effort and are primarily focused on relaxation, mental rest, or entertainment. Watching a live performance at a theater fits this description perfectly, as it involves sitting and observing without engaging in physical activity. <br/>  <br/> On the other hand, walking through a garden, though relatively gentle, is an active form of recreation because it requires physical movement. Going for a run and playing tennis are both vigorous active recreational activities that demand significant physical exertion and skill. <br/>  <br/> Passive recreation is essential for mental relaxation and recovery from stress, providing a balance to more physically demanding activities.</div>", "topic": "RECREATION, LEISURE AND DANCE: RECREATION AND LEISURE : TYPES OF RECREATIONAL ACTIVITIES"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A person who exercises regularly is more likely to have a lower risk of falls as they age due to improvements in which two fitness components?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Flexibility and muscular strength.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Body composition and cardiovascular endurance.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Muscular endurance and reaction time.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Speed and agility.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">As people age, maintaining flexibility and muscular strength becomes crucial in reducing the risk of falls. Flexibility improves the range of motion in joints, allowing older adults to move more freely and avoid awkward movements that could cause loss of balance. Muscular strength enhances the ability to stabilize the body and react to shifts in posture, especially when recovering from trips or slips. <br/>  <br/> While other components like reaction time and agility also contribute to fall prevention, flexibility and strength form the foundational physical capabilities that support balance and stability. Good body composition and cardiovascular endurance improve overall health but have less direct influence on fall prevention. Therefore, regular exercise focusing on strength training and flexibility exercises, such as resistance workouts and stretching, is essential for fall risk reduction in older adults.</div>", "topic": "PHYSICAL FITNESS AND CONDITIONING PROGRAMMES: PHYSICAL FITNESS : BENEFITS OF PHYSICAL ACTIVITY AND EXERCISE"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What role do medical check-ups play in controlling communicable diseases?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Identifying cases early and initiating timely treatment</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Encouraging self-medication without diagnosis</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Ignoring symptoms until they worsen</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Limiting access to vaccinations</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Early diagnosis through check-ups reduces disease transmission by isolating cases and providing treatment. It supports vaccination and public health measures to control outbreaks effectively.</div>", "topic": "PERSONAL, COMMUNITY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH: PERSONAL HEALTH : METHOD OF PROMOTION AND MAINTENANCE OF PERSONAL HEALTH –EXERCISE, NUTRITION, REGULAR MEDICAL CHECK-UP;"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What is one of the key indicators a physical education teacher would look for to identify potential scoliosis in a student?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">One shoulder or hip appearing higher than the other.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A rounded, hunchback appearance of the upper back.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A collapsed arch in the foot.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An inward curvature of the lower back.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Scoliosis is characterized by an abnormal lateral curvature of the spine. One of the most noticeable signs, especially during physical examination in a school setting, is asymmetry in the shoulders or hips — where one shoulder or hip appears visibly higher or more prominent than the other. This unevenness results from the sideways bending and rotation of the spine.</div>", "topic": "HUMAN ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY IN RELATION TO PHE: SOMATOTYPES AND POSTURE : TYPES OF POSTURAL DEFECT –FLATFOOT, SCOLIOSIS, KYPHOSIS, LORDOSIS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is a key characteristic of 'rest'?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It is a purposeful activity done for personal enjoyment.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It is a time of conscious or unconscious inactivity for recovery.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It is an obligation that a person must do.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It involves high-intensity physical activity.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rest refers to periods when the body and mind reduce activity levels to recover from physical or mental exertion. It can be conscious (like sitting or lying down to relax) or unconscious (such as sleep). Rest is essential for repairing tissues, restoring energy, and maintaining overall health. Unlike recreation, which involves active enjoyment, rest is primarily about inactivity and recovery. It is not an obligation in the strict sense but a biological necessity. High-intensity physical activity is the opposite of rest.</div>", "topic": "RECREATION, LEISURE AND DANCE: RECREATION AND LEISURE : DEFINITION AND IMPORTANCE OF RECREATION, LEISURE, WORK AND REST"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What is the first thing you should do when encountering a person with a severe, open wound?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Wash the wound with water and mild soap.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Apply pressure to the wound with a clean cloth or bandage.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Call for emergency medical help immediately.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Suture the wound closed to stop the bleeding.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When faced with a severe, open wound that is bleeding heavily, the priority is to control the bleeding to prevent shock or excessive blood loss. Applying firm, direct pressure with a clean cloth or bandage helps the blood to clot and slows or stops the bleeding. While calling for emergency help is crucial, immediate bleeding control takes precedence to preserve life.</div>", "topic": "FIRST AID AND SAFETY EDUCATION: FIRST AID : COMMON INJURIES THAT REQUIRE FIRST AID – CUTS, WOUND, SPRAIN, STRAIN, DISLOCATION, FRACTURE"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What corrective strategy best manages flatfoot?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Use orthotic insoles paired with regular intrinsic foot muscle strengthening.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Wear flexible flat shoes that allow natural flattening of the foot arch.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Avoid walking barefoot on hard surfaces at all times to prevent collapse.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Reduce physical activity significantly to avoid foot muscle fatigue.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Flatfoot, or pes planus, occurs when the medial longitudinal arch of the foot collapses, causing the entire sole to come into contact with the ground. This condition can lead to pain, altered gait, and increased risk of injuries up the kinetic chain, such as knee or hip problems. The best corrective strategy focuses on both supporting the arch and strengthening the muscles that maintain it. <br/>  <br/> Orthotic insoles provide external support by elevating the arch, redistributing pressure more evenly across the foot, and improving alignment during walking or running. This mechanical correction helps reduce strain on the soft tissues and joints of the foot. <br/>  <br/> However, orthotics alone are insufficient. The intrinsic foot muscles, especially those supporting the arch, need to be strengthened to provide active, dynamic support. Exercises like toe curls, marble pickups, and towel scrunches help improve muscular endurance and control, making the arch more resilient over time. <br/>  <br/> In contrast, wearing flexible flat shoes can allow the arch to collapse further, worsening symptoms. Avoiding barefoot walking on hard surfaces can help reduce stress but does not address the underlying weakness. Reducing physical activity might decrease discomfort temporarily but ultimately leads to muscle weakening and poorer foot function. <br/>  <br/> Thus, a combined approach of orthotic support with targeted strengthening exercises is the most effective long-term management for flatfoot.</div>", "topic": "HUMAN ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY IN RELATION TO PHE: SOMATOTYPES AND POSTURE : CAUSES AND CORRECTIVE MEASURES OF POSTURAL DEFECTS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is considered the most important component of physical fitness for overall health? <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Muscular strength</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cardiorespiratory endurance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Balance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Speed</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Cardiorespiratory endurance, also known as cardiovascular endurance, is widely considered the most important component of physical fitness for overall health. It refers to the ability of the heart, lungs, and blood vessels to deliver oxygen efficiently to working muscles during sustained physical activity. Good cardiorespiratory endurance improves the efficiency of the cardiovascular and respiratory systems, which helps reduce the risk of chronic diseases such as heart disease, stroke, diabetes, and hypertension. <br/>  <br/> While muscular strength, balance, and speed are important for specific activities and injury prevention, they do not have as direct an impact on overall cardiovascular health and longevity as cardiorespiratory endurance does. Muscular strength supports joint health and functional ability, balance helps prevent falls, and speed improves quickness and reaction time. However, without adequate cardiorespiratory endurance, overall health and stamina may be compromised.</div>", "topic": "PHYSICAL FITNESS AND CONDITIONING PROGRAMMES: PHYSICAL FITNESS : DEFINITION OF PHYSICAL FITNESS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which bone is involved in forming the shoulder joint?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Scapula</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Humerus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Clavicle</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">All of the above</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The shoulder joint is a complex structure involving the humerus (upper arm bone), scapula (shoulder blade), and clavicle (collarbone). The head of the humerus fits into the glenoid cavity of the scapula, forming the ball-and-socket joint, while the clavicle stabilizes the shoulder girdle and connects the arm to the torso. Together, these bones enable the wide range of motion seen in the shoulder.</div>", "topic": "HUMAN ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY IN RELATION TO PHE: SKELETAL SYSTEM : BONES AND JOINTS INVOLVED IN MOVEMENT"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What is the importance of having qualified officials and referees in national sports competitions?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They ensure impartial enforcement of rules and uphold competition integrity.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They primarily manage team logistics and athlete accommodations.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They focus on promoting the sport's image through media appearances.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">They encourage spectators to participate in cheering and event activities.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Qualified officials and referees play a crucial role in maintaining fairness and order during national sports competitions. Their primary responsibility is to apply the rules accurately and impartially, which ensures that all participants compete on a level playing field. This impartial enforcement protects the integrity of the sport by preventing cheating, unfair advantages, and disputes that could undermine the competition's legitimacy.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL SPORTS COMPETITIONS: SPORTS COMPETITIONS AT NATIONAL LEVEL : ORGANISATION AND ADMINISTRATION OF SPORTS COMPETITIONS"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which badminton grip is used for powerful overhead shots like clears and smashes?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Panhandle grip</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Forehand grip</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Backhand grip</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Universal grip</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The forehand grip in badminton is the primary grip used to execute powerful overhead shots such as clears and smashes. This grip allows players to generate maximum racket head speed and control, making it ideal for delivering forceful and precise shots. With the forehand grip, the hand holds the racket handle loosely but firmly, enabling a quick wrist snap and full arm rotation necessary for power and accuracy.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: RACKET GAMES –TABLE TENNIS AND BADMINTON : SKILLS IN TABLE TENNIS AND BADMINTON"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What is the main function of the 'shin guards' worn by football players?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To improve a player's speed and agility.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To provide extra support for the ankle joint.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To protect the player's lower legs from kicks and impacts.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To give the player a better grip on the ball with their feet.</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Shin guards are a crucial piece of protective equipment in football, designed specifically to shield the lower legs—particularly the shinbone (tibia)—from injuries caused by direct contact such as kicks, collisions, or accidental impacts during the game. The lower legs are vulnerable during tackles and challenges, so shin guards help prevent bruises, cuts, fractures, and other serious injuries.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: BALL GAMES -FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL : FACILITIES AND EQUIPMENT IN FOOTBALL AND BASKETBALL"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In badminton, what is the consequence if a player touches the net with their racket during a rally?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The player wins the point.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The player loses the point.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The rally continues as normal.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The opponent must replay the point.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Touching the net with the racket, body, or clothing during a rally is considered a fault in badminton. The opposing side immediately wins the point. This rule ensures players maintain proper court etiquette and avoid unfair advantages by encroaching on the opponent's space.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: RACKET GAMES –TABLE TENNIS AND BADMINTON : RULES, REGULATION AND OFFICIATING IN TABLE TENNIS AND BADMINTON"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What is the standard height of a badminton net at the center of the court?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.55 meters</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.524 meters</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.40 meters</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1.60 meters</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Badminton World Federation (BWF) sets the standard net height at 1.524 meters (5 feet) at the center of the court. This height balances offensive and defensive play, ensuring a fair challenge for players to clear or smash the shuttlecock.</div>", "topic": "THEORY OF PRACTICE OF SPORTS AND GAMES: RACKET GAMES –TABLE TENNIS AND BADMINTON : SPECIFICATION OF FACILITIES AND EQUIPMENT IN TABLE TENNIS AND BADMINTON"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ISSF is the international governing body for which sport?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">International Shooting Sport Federation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">International Sailing Sport Federation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">International Swimming Sport Federation</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">International Skating Sport Federation</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The ISSF stands for International Shooting Sport Federation, which is the global governing body responsible for the administration and regulation of shooting sports. It oversees disciplines such as rifle, pistol, and shotgun shooting in international competitions, including the Olympic Games. The ISSF sets the rules, organizes world championships, and promotes the development of shooting sports worldwide. The other options—sailing, swimming, and skating—are governed by different international federations, such as World Sailing, FINA (Fédération Internationale de Natation), and the International Skating Union (ISU), respectively.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL SPORTS COMPETITIONS: INTERNATIONAL SPORTS COMPETITIONS AND THE GOVERNING BODIES : ALL AFRICA GAMES"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is an example of health promotion?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Vaccination campaigns to prevent infectious diseases</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Emergency surgery for accident victims</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Prescription of antibiotics for infections</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Rehabilitation after a stroke</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Vaccination campaigns are proactive measures aimed at preventing disease before it occurs, which aligns perfectly with health promotion goals. Emergency surgery and rehabilitation are treatments after illness or injury and fall under medical care rather than health promotion.</div>", "topic": "FOUNDATIONS AND PRINCIPLES OF PHYSICAL AND HEALTH EDUCATION: PHILOSOPHY, OBJECTIVES AND SETTINGS OF HEALTH EDUCATION : MEANING OF HEALTH PROMOTION"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What is the defining characteristic of a 'single-parent family'?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The family has a single income.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The family is led by a single adult.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The family has a single child.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The family lives in a single house.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A single-parent family is one in which either the mother or the father is the sole head of the household, responsible for raising the children without the presence of the other parent. This can result from various circumstances such as divorce, separation, death of a partner, or choice. The defining feature is the single adult acting as the primary caregiver, not factors like income level, number of children, or type of housing. Single-parent families may face unique challenges, such as balancing work and caregiving, but can still provide a stable, loving, and supportive environment for children.</div>", "topic": "FAMILY LIFE AND HUMAN SEXUALITY EDUCATION: FAMILY : DEFINITION AND TYPES"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Why is collaboration between orthodox and traditional health service providers important in community health?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It eliminates the need for modern hospitals entirely</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It ensures patients are only treated by traditional methods</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It improves cultural acceptance and increases access to care</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It reduces the need for trained medical professionals</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When orthodox and traditional practitioners work together, communities benefit from both cultural familiarity and modern scientific care. For example, TBAs can refer complicated births to hospitals, while orthodox practitioners can respect and incorporate safe traditional practices to increase trust and cooperation in the community.</div>", "topic": "PERSONAL, COMMUNITY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH: COMMUNITY HEALTH : COMMUNITY HEALTH SERVICES –PROVIDERS OF HEALTH SERVICES (ORTHODOX SERVICES, TRADITIONAL SERVICES –BONE SETTERS, BIRTH ATTENDANCE)"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In precolonial Nigeria, wrestling served primarily as:</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A casual pastime with no community significance.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A cultural, social, and physical training activity.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A sport imported from neighboring countries.</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A religious ritual without physical benefits.</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In precolonial Nigeria, wrestling was more than just a sport — it was a key part of cultural identity and community life. It was often performed during festivals, initiation ceremonies, and communal gatherings. Wrestling helped young men develop physical strength, agility, and endurance while fostering respect, discipline, and social bonds. It also served as preparation for hunting, defense, and other physically demanding aspects of life.</div>", "topic": "FOUNDATIONS AND PRINCIPLES OF PHYSICAL AND HEALTH EDUCATION: PRINCIPLES, MEANING, SCOPE AND PHILOSOPHY OF PHYSICAL EDUCATION (PE) : HISTORY AND DEVELOPMENT OF PE IN PRECOLONIAL, COLONIAL AND POST-COLONIAL ERAS IN NIGERIA"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which of the following is an example of visual pollution?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Litter scattered across public parks</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Excessive carbon emissions from factories</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">High-pitched sounds from traffic horns</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Oil leakage into rivers</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Visual pollution refers to unattractive or unpleasant visual elements in the environment, such as litter, graffiti, or poorly maintained structures. It affects community pride, tourism, and the enjoyment of recreational spaces.</div>", "topic": "PERSONAL, COMMUNITY AND ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH: ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH : POLLUTION"}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which organ is part of both the respiratory and digestive systems?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Trachea</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Pharynx</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Esophagus</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Larynx</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The pharynx serves as a passageway for both air (to the lungs) and food (to the stomach). This dual function makes it part of both the respiratory and digestive systems. The trachea and larynx belong solely to the respiratory system, while the esophagus belongs to the digestive system.</div>", "topic": "HUMAN ANATOMY AND PHYSIOLOGY IN RELATION TO PHE: CELLS, TISSUES AND SYSTEMS OF THE HUMAN BODY : ORGANS AND SYSTEMS OF THE HUMAN BODY."}, {"id": "objective>PHE>2025 Model I>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Which edition of the All Africa Games was the first to include athletes with disabilities?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">1995 in Harare, Zimbabwe</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2003 in Abuja, Nigeria</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2011 in Maputo, Mozambique</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">2015 in Brazzaville, Republic of the Congo</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The 10th edition of the All Africa Games, held in Maputo, Mozambique, in 2011, was the first time that athletes with disabilities were included in the official program. This was a significant step forward for the Games, which had previously only included able-bodied athletes. This move to integrate para-sports was in line with international trends and the growing movement to promote inclusivity in sports.</div>", "topic": "NATIONAL AND INTERNATIONAL SPORTS COMPETITIONS: INTERNATIONAL SPORTS COMPETITIONS AND THE GOVERNING BODIES : ALL AFRICA GAMES"}];
